Here are a few points to consider with that regular expression and its usage in your “if ( input.match(...) )” check:

1) Match vs. Test  
   • In JavaScript, input.match(regex) returns an array (or null) of matches. If you just want to verify whether the input contains (or fully matches) a pattern, regex.test(...) is often more straightforward since it returns a boolean. For example:  
     if (regex.test(input)) {
       // valid
     } else {
       // invalid
     }

2) Multiline & Special Characters  
   • Your pattern is spread across multiple lines and includes backslashes, triple backticks, and other symbols. JavaScript’s string-literal rules might interpret those backslashes in unintended ways. Also, newlines inside a regular expression can break it unless handled carefully.  
   • If you truly need to match across multiple lines, consider adding the "m" (multiline) or "s" (dotall) flags or rewriting your pattern into a single line (sometimes using the RegExp constructor with a string literal that includes \n if needed).  
   • Make sure any literal triple backticks (` ``` `) are escaped in the regex if they must be matched literally. Similarly, watch out for stray backslashes since they might need to be doubled inside a JavaScript string.

3) Anchors (^ and $) vs. “Contains”  
   • Decide whether you need to match the entire input exactly or just detect that the required text is somewhere inside the input. If you want the entire input to match exactly, you typically wrap your pattern with ^ and $ and remove the g flag:  
     const pattern = /^#\s+[pP][rR][oO] ... [yY][oO][uU]\s+[mM][aA][yY]\s+[aA][lL][sS][oO]\s+[aA][dD][dD]\s*: ...$/im;  
     if (pattern.test(input)) {
       processRequest(input);
     } else {
       reject("Invalid format");
     }
   • If you only need to confirm that the snippet appears anywhere inside the string, then your current approach with partial matches is fine (but you could still simplify by using .test() instead of .match()).

4) Case Insensitivity  
   • You already use [pP][rR]... etc. manually, but including the i flag (/.../i) is typically simpler. For example, for “Prohibition” you can simply write /prohibition/gi instead of [pP][rR][oO]....

5) Keeping It Manageable  
   • Because your pattern is large, consider constructing it step by step in a multiline string (with backticks) and then passing it into new RegExp(...)—this lets you see the pattern more clearly and reduce escaping errors. For example:  
     const patternString = `
       #\\s+prohibition\\s+era
       [\\s\\S]*?           // some pattern to match everything in between
       [yY][oO][uU]\\s+[mM][aA][yY]\\s+[aA][lL][sS][oO]\\s+[aA][dD][dD]\\s*:
       ...
     `.trim();
     const pattern = new RegExp(patternString, "i");  
   • Then you can adapt it to match precisely what you need, including literal newlines, triple backticks, etc.

Summary of Recommendations  
• Use .test(...) instead of .match(...) if you only want a boolean pass/fail.  
• If the entire string must match exactly, include ^...$ and remove the g flag.  
• Handle multiline or special symbols carefully (possibly with "m" or "s" flags, or by explicitly including \n, \`\`\`, etc.).  
• Consider using case-insensitive (i) rather than writing out [pP][rR][oO]... for readability.  

By refining these points, you’ll make your validation more robust and easier to maintain.
